insta_description:
Happy St Patty‚Äôs Day friends! Mama isn‚Äôt much of a ‚Äúbuy festive shirts or outfits‚Äù kinda gal so you all get this very classic moss green gap shirt and my lovebug ready to rip apart the clovers I made for the community clover hunt during this time of ‚Äòsocial distancing‚Äô.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
For last few days we‚Äôve spent our time inside having dance parties, playing ball, building with blocks and legos, reading, wrestling, and learning new words. Sadly, this weather isn‚Äôt making for the best outdoor time and Jax has most definitely been stir-crazy and fussy‚ÄîI think he‚Äôs growing! He‚Äôs also napping for much longer periods and catching onto more concepts that are more mischievous than anything! I really don‚Äôt know what I got myself into with this little toddler but I‚Äôm mentally trying to prepare myself and I‚Äôm seriously itching for summer to get here so we can go outside and he can run amuck! ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Lucky for us, today we got to go outside! We did some cleaning in the garage and took a drive just to get out. Didn‚Äôt really go anywhere but that‚Äôs what this ‚Äòsocial isolation‚Äô thing is all about and we‚Äôre doing our part! ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
We hope you‚Äôre all taking advantage of this time to simply slow down and spend time with loved ones. In reality, many of us never get this precious time and even when we do, we‚Äôre still in that GO-mode. I know it‚Äôs difficult to be told to just shut it off but I think if we can change our perspective on it, it isn‚Äôt so bad. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
I also realize everyone has a different situation so some of us may be struggling more than others. If you‚Äôre one of these individuals, please reach out. There are so many good people in our community who are willing to lend a helping hand. And even if it‚Äôs just anxiety or fear of isolation and loneliness, speak up! There are many modes of communication and I‚Äôm happy to be a friendly connection.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
With all of that said, I hope we can all continue to practice this ‚Äòsocial isolation‚Äô thing as best as we can. It‚Äôs important because this will determine the future of how this all plays out. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Stay kind friends! Let‚Äôs connect from a distance and share tips on how to keep our littles entertained as well as keep ourselves sane.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£

Conium maculatum also know as Hemlock is found almost everywhere in Monterey County. Hemlock is a highly poisonous plant which is fatal if ingested. It is closely related to carrots which leads some people confuse it with a wild herb or vegetable ‚ò†Ô∏è so be careful especially when hiking with children or pets that like to munch. An easy way to identify hemlock is by looking at the stems in which you will see reddish brown speckles, also known called the ‚Äúblood of Socrates‚Äù. Socrates was a famous Greek philosopher who was sentenced to death by Hemlock poisoning. The American Molossus breed, here soon @heavyweightmolossus

5000 years BC, at a time much different than ours, it was a time where only the strong survived. A time where people were nomadic, barbaric and when they wanted land, riches, steel and even people they would just take it. A dark time and a time where people needed to have defense. They needed something that would protect the women and children left behind while men were hunting or at war. They needed comfort and peace of mind. They needed The Molossus. The American Molossus is the resurrected ancient guardian¬† of antiquity.

This giant close quarter guardian was brought back using the true descendants of the ancient breed. The historical close quarter guardian was created and bred by Man as far back as 5000 BC in Sumer, Babylon, Mesopotamia, Ancient Greece where the reference name "Nasaru Urbat" translated to Guard Dog of Death was changed to the Molossus and was used to protect the villages, people, children and other animals from predators and enemies. This huge guardian was bred to deter and guard. Unlike other dogs used for hunting or travel this dog was strictly for close quarter guarding as documented. They are referenced down to the ancient cropping of the large toes. This would certainly indicate the need for the dog to stay close.

It feels like the world is being turned inside out and upside down. 
I‚Äôve been spending most of my newly freed up time reflecting and observing as the shifting tide sways and grows. 
Uncertainty is everywhere but we can still choose to remain focused on the things that we can control:

Social distancing is all of our responsibility  to enforce when possible.

Honor other people‚Äôs feelings and reactions without judgement.

Be kind and patient with everyone. Especially yourself.

Take extra care of yourself physically, emotionally and spiritually.

Wash your hands. A lot.

Take time to quiet your mind and just BREATHE.

Exercise, meditate, dance, play, cuddle, cry.

Call a loved one.

Remember that we are all in this together and that we are all feeling the repercussions on every level.

Everyone is being effected financially, emotionally or otherwise in ways that are far reaching and the unknown lingers around us like a fog.

I have felt the direct impact of the event industry being all but shut down for an undetermined amount of time. 
My heart goes out to our local communities, nation and entire planet during this unprecedented crisis and I sincerely send healing prayers to all.

I‚Äôm still making a game plan for an interim income source that will most likely include online dance, fitness and wellness coaching. Also dabbling in creating an interactive kid‚Äôs series for our little ones!
 Any feedback or suggestions are welcome.

These times are getting rough for some of us out there! My workplace was shut down, I‚Äôm left with small part-time minimum wage checks and I have to use up all of my sick days just to have some money in my pocket. There‚Äôs no official start date for that job and I know I‚Äôm not the

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm so thankful for Monat. If I hadn‚Äôt said ‚Äúyes‚Äù to this opportunity, I would literally have no back up income to help me right now. 
This job has given me purpose and a clearer path of what I want in life. I want to help people feel confident and happy in these dark times. And I can do all of this by working wherever and whenever I want. Since this whole ‚ÄòShelter In Place‚Äô thing started, I felt relief knowing that my other source of income can help pay for necessities like food & water.

I‚Äôm blessed to be a part of this organization with other likeminded individuals who want to build their dream life one day at a time. insta_description:
We went green in a whole new way this St Patrick‚Äôs Day...üçÄ üòâ üçÄ üòÄ üçÄ

I stumbled upon this unique tour while I was looking up the Top Ten Things to do in Palm Springs - one of my favorite quick Google searches anytime we land in a new city. ‚Å£
‚Å£
It‚Äôs the only one of its kind in the country and gives visitors a chance to get up close and personal with those crazy huge windmills you pass as you drive across the country time after time. üòâ We‚Äôve always been curious about them, and been in full support of renewable energy options, so I quickly reserved four spots for our family at the Palm Springs Windmill Tours.‚Å£
‚Å£
Let me tell you - the experience was awesome!! While we couldn‚Äôt go inside one ourselves (safety reasons), we began our tour with a video that took us inside and along for a day with one of the operators that services the machines.‚Å£
‚Å£
Then we loaded into a bus and rode around the property, peering up into the sky as we learned all about the history of the machines, the way they work, and how exactly they harness the power of the wind. We also got to see their massive size up close - which is very impressive! These things are huge!! The largest wind turbine was 270 feet to the Nacelle (that little room sitting at the top) and had blades that stretched 137 feet. From ground to tip that means you‚Äôre looking at an impressive 407 foot tall windmill! üò≥ ‚Å£
‚Å£
We wrapped up the tour with date shakes (YUM!) and a whole new appreciation for these awesome renewable energy wind farms.‚Å£
‚Å£
Have you ever seen a wind turbine up close?‚Å£
‚Å£

accessibility_caption: Image may contain: drink
insta_description:
I forever stand by my belief that Carignan is one of the best grapes (and is definitely one of my personal favorite wines). I owe all of that to @marthastoumen. My world was forever changed the day I had Post Flirtation. The second time it was rocked was after receiving my first wine club shipment from her, which included a bottle of Carignan.
.
Originally a Spanish varietal, it became more widely popular in France. In the States, it was originally a blending grape rarely used on its own. Until recently, when many new winemakers got their hands on the abundance of it found growing on old vines in Mendocino County.
.
Carignan is a great fall wine with its strong cranberry profile. But I love it year round. It‚Äôs juicy when it‚Äôs chilled in the summer. And totally comforting when served closer to a standard red (mid-60s) in the cooler months.
.
And when I say cranberry, I don‚Äôt mean make your mouth pucker cranberry. Martha‚Äôs Carignan is bright, with balanced-acid. Low tannins, which when paired with the acid is a delightful dance on your tongue. The cranberry is your grandma‚Äôs homemade cranberry sauce without all the sugar. You only wish you had green bean casserole with dinner tonight for it be a perfect match. I‚Äôve got vegetarian tacos, so I‚Äôm golden.
.
Moral of my long Instagram story? Find yourself some Carignan. @marthastoumen and @vincaminorwine both produce delicious ones. @lasjaraswines has one too. All three are low intervention. And, all three let you order direct, in case you can‚Äôt find it locally. .
.

1 YEAR AND A HALF IN THE USA ~ üí´
18 MONTHS
547 DAYS .
üéµ„ÄäEach step I left behind
Each road you know is mine
Walking on the line ten stories high
Say you'll still be by my side „Äã üí´üöÄ
~Beautiful Crime
.
Here I am now, after 1 year and 6 months of life in the US, in my house in San Francisco... in quarantine.ü¶† If you had told me in september 2018 where I would be in march 2020, I would have never guess being in quarantine because of a deadly virus ü§£ But I would have never guess neither living in San Francisco, with my 3rd host family and in my 9 months extension ! I had a lot of hopes and expectations coming here, then of course I had a lot of disappointment but so much more joy ! Some of my biggest dreams came true, and some that I hadn't plan did too, I met sooooo many wonderful people, I checked a lot of destinations from my bucket list and went also to so many places I hadn't plan to but they turned out to be a great suprise ! So even after more than a year of this life, it still continue to suprise me, although now I know that the life of an au pair can be summed up by this word : suprises. The good ones and the bad ones. So far, I am very grateful for all the suprises I got, even the bad ones, because they all led me here, where I am super happy now. Although recently all the au pairs and the whole world got a really bad suprise, I'm trying to be positive because this whole year and a half showed me how many good things can come from something bad ! So, I'm crossing my fingers really tight and hope for one more good suprise before the end of my time in the US ! üôèü§ûüòä .

I would like to host a FREE online yoga class open to all levels! ..
Many of us are staying in to protect ourselves and the community. As frustrating and even isolating it can be, there is always an opportunity to stop and take a breather. By putting down my stress and anxiety, I can think clearly and do the things I need to do from a grounded place. ..
..
I‚Äôm seeing a lot of teachers and studios offering online options and it‚Äôs beautiful to see everyone putting their best foot forward to support in these trying times. It‚Äôs been amazingly helpful for me to practice everyday with a community through online class, and I‚Äôd like to share that gift in the way that I can!
..
..
Let me know what your time zone is and what time is preferable for you! I will update soon on exact date and time as I get more info!! I hope you join and share cyber space with me!!
..

insta_description:
Part of me doesn‚Äôt want to search for a silver lining in the midst of the most trying times for many of us. I know I‚Äôve never seen something like this in my life, no one really has. I‚Äôve never seen people so fearful, but in the past couple days I‚Äôve never seen us so connected. We‚Äôre navigating these uncharted waters, upended from our normal lives, scared of the unknown, but we‚Äôre coming together and picking up those who need help most. When it ends, and it will end, I hope we look back on these times and don‚Äôt see it as a wasted opportunity. I didn‚Äôt intend for it to be a hoo-rah speech, more so a reminder that you can make the most of this temporary pause in routine. Here‚Äôs a few things I‚Äôm trying to do to keep my mind clear and focused on the future:
1) Call that relative or friend you‚Äôve been meaning to catch up with. They‚Äôre likely going through this too and will appreciate your call
2) Check in on yourself! How are you feeling? Is this a chance to catch up on much needed sleep? Take care of your body and mind during this chaotic time. Eating healthy and exercise makes a world of a difference.
3) Social distancing doesn‚Äôt mean solitary confinement. Try to get some fresh air, go on a walk, and get some sun.
4) Think about the future. It‚Äôs easy to dwell on negative news, use this opportunity to organize your career, house, business, etc and when things get back to normal, you‚Äôll hit the ground running.

I have some more tips pinned on my profile that will hopefully help as well. As always, shoot me an email or message if you need anything!

insta_description:
One of my first memories: I was 6yrs old, watching people on the news in Russia, they were standing in a very long line for bread. My parents explained a child‚Äôs version of what was going on there, that memory always, always stuck with me. The over abundance in the west comes at a price, although we don‚Äôt see that upfront and personal. We fight wars that are half way across the globe that we are blind to. This global pandemic reminds us all, I would think, how connected we are, and in many ways how fragile. Swipe right to see those empty shelves right here in America, not 1980s Russia (my love, a country I love deeply too). These are my @sonyimages snappers from last night before our citywide shut down. Stay safe, stay isolated. Flatten the curve.

insta_description: The Los Angeles County Sheriff‚Äôs Department is releasing inmates from its jails and cutting down on how many people it books into custody to protect those housed in close quarters from the growing coronavirus pandemic. Sheriff Alex Villanueva said deputies and police officers across the county have been directed to cite and release people whenever possible, instead of arresting them, and to seek medical clearance before booking anyone who shows symptoms. Countywide, he said, arrests have dropped from a daily average of 300 to 60, while the jail population was reduced by more than 600 inmates. He said that since Feb. 28, the Sheriff‚Äôs Department had reduced the jail population to 16,459 inmates, including through the early release of inmates who had less than 30 days of jail time left to serve. Deputies may now cite and release anyone whose total bail would amount to less than $50,000. ‚ÄúWe‚Äôve raised it from $25,000 to $50,000,‚Äù Villanueva said. ‚ÄúAnother way we‚Äôre reducing the population.‚Äù #cdcr #california #inmates #incarcerated #covid_19 #covid19 #coronavirus #earlyrelease #staysafeyall üôèüèΩ #pursuitofjustice ‚öñÔ∏è

Seeing as insta forces multiple-photo posts into portrait mode, the shelter-in-places are quickly accumulating, dives are getting cancelled, and everything is changing by the day (if not hour), over the next few days I‚Äôll try to post some of my best photos from this last weekend individually.

Underwater I thought this would be my best shot of the weekend - the contrast yet proximity between the group of urchins (who aren‚Äôt properly social distancing ü§î) and the kelp forest here got me thinking about the shockingly rapid transitions between urchin barren and kelp forest communities we‚Äôve seen in the past half-decade, and how that‚Äôs kind of analogous to the rapid transitions we‚Äôre all forced to deal with now. Hopefully we can get back to some normalcy soon and get back into the water, observing and studying these changes... but until then I guess we need to live vicariously from past photos; stay safe, support each other, and don‚Äôt get too stir crazy!  #kelpforest @reefcheckcalifornia #divewithpurpose @live2divescubaco #California #Monterey #uwphotography #scuba #scubadiving

Driving from the far end of Yolo Bypass Wildlife Area to the entrance after a day of reading and reflection by the wetlands. As someone who strongly dislikes being indoors, I frequently go over to Yolo Bypass, which is close to my apartment, to get reading and non-studio work done in an environment where I can focus better, creating a temporary outdoor office space. insta_description: Over the weekend, judges in Cleveland, Ohio, became some of the first to really take these warnings to heart: A county court held emergency hearings to let dozens of jail detainees go home early, with the goal of sending hundreds more back to their communities as soon as possible. In San Francisco, meanwhile, attorneys are also trying to release more people from lockup. Last week, the city‚Äôs public defender announced his office would ask courts to immediately free anyone sentenced to county jail with less than six months remaining on their sentence, as well as all clients held pretrial who are at heightened risk for getting sick‚Äîa fairly large group, given that many people booked into jails have preexisting health conditions. The city‚Äôs new chief prosecutor, Chesa Boudin, said he would not oppose the release of pretrial detainees facing misdemeanor charges or drug-related felony charges as long as they pose no threat to public safety. He urged his team of prosecutors to help more people leave confinement early by offering plea deals that take into account the time they have already waited in jail. Other jurisdictions around the country are trying to slow the speed at which people are jailed in other ways. Some are postponing nonessential criminal court hearings, unless the defendant is already in custody. Sheriffs in some counties are urging police not to put people into jail who are accused of nonviolent crimes or misdemeanors. insta_description:
Repost from @susiesseniordogs
‚Ä¢
FOSTER SPONSORSHIPS! SSD will cover your cost to foster a senior dog during the COVID-19 period! ü¶†

This offer is for anyone in the United States who will be home from work/school/life for the foreseeable future and will have some time to foster a dog. On top of the typical need for fosters and adopters, right now shelters will be even more overcrowded, understaffed and with limited or no volunteers. Uncertain times also results in more in owner surrenders and intake numbers. Now is the time to foster! Fostering a dog is a great way to help the system as well as provide you a little pick-me-up during these isolating days. 
Some rescues and shelters are able to cover the costs for fosters, but many are not‚Äî and that's where SSD wants to step in during our current crisis. If you have the ability to foster but are worried about added expenses, SSD will cover the costs of any food, supplies and/or medications for however long you are able to foster!

1) Fostering MUST take place through a 501c3 rescue group or shelter. 
2) Dogs MUST be age 6 years old and up (typically, we consider "senior" status age 7, but making exceptions). 3) Once you are an approved foster, email susie.doggie@gmail.com and include your rescue/shelter contact on the email, too. SSD will mail supplies directly to the foster OR reimburse the rescue/shelter upon receipt. 
4) That's it! Email with any questions! ü¶†üßºü¶†üßºü¶† #seniordogs #fostering #adoptdontshop #foster #dog #doggy #shelterdog #ilovedogs #dogsofinstagram #instadog #california #coronavirus #covid_19 #help #save #helpme #saveme #love

insta_description: About 2 months ago, I went with a friend to the Winchester Mystery House!! (Finally)... I heard about this place in high school, and in general, glad I could see what it was all about. For starters -Yes, I do believe it is haunted... while waiting for the tour to start, I was standing in the back and I witnessed one of the glass doors slowly open automatically on its own (an entrance we didn‚Äôt end up going through). And another incident, about 20 minutes into the tour, I was standing in a room in the attic and yet again, another window opened on its own, while the 3 other windows next to it weren‚Äôt affected or nudged at all? Again, both instances could‚Äôve just been the wind somehow, but later we were taken into a room where Sarah Winchester apparently used to have s√©ances!! Like people, I didn‚Äôt know this tour was that wild.. I felt my stomach turn, but thankfully we didn‚Äôt stay in that creepy room too long, (she kept it unfinished because she would mainly go in there at night, with candles and her ‚Äúpsychic reader assistant.‚Äù The story of the house goes; After Sarah and her husband lost their daughter Annie a couple months after birth, the father in-law passed away, and then shortly after her husband also died, so she believed she was cursed and it was because of the -as she calls ‚Äúblood money‚Äù from the firearm business her husband owned. She thought the ghosts wanted revenge, so she reached out to a fortune üîÆ teller for advice and was told to move out west, and to appease the spirits, she must create rooms for them, but also, she was afraid of being directly contacted by them, so she tried to also confuse them by having built hallways and stairs that went no where, or would just take you into circles. On the tour they don‚Äôt take you through the whole house, just the main areas. Oh, and when the big Earthquake in 1906 happened, she thought that was because the ghosts were angry at her for not building enough space, or fast enough, and the world had to suffer because of her, so she took rebuilding her home even more seriously after that. So crazy!! And the current staff mentioned that they have also seen ghosts that resemble past servants that used to work there.

Waves pushing further inward
As the sun sets
On what could potentially be
Our last days of normalcy 
I could spend eternity here
Walking in the wet sand
As the water embraces my bare feet

Mementos are littered across the beach
These rocks, shells, broken glass
Resist the pull of the water
Beckoning them back into the sea

I collect them
Each with uniques stories
If only they could tell

Where have you been?
Oh the adventures
Centuries long you must have endured

Tell me
What is to be expected of our future?
Do we have one?
At least one to look forward to?

I see smiling faces all around
I hear subtle laugher in the air
But how soon shall those disappear
Like footprints swallowed by the tide?

More and more mementos
Are returning to sea
I saved as many as I could
Before my cold feet return 
To the harsh pavement
